<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-12-04T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-12-04T00:00:00-05:00" n="1834" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1834">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 767.70/190.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of the Navy</gloss>
                                to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi>.</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Navy Department</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-12-04">
                                    <hi rend="italic">December 4, 1912</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to quote for the
                            information of the Department of State the following extract from a
                            cablegram dated December 4, 1912, received from the Commanding Officer
                            of the U. S. S. <hi rend="italic">Scorpion</hi> at Constantinople,
                            Turkey:</p>
                        <p>“Yesterday men reembarked.”</p>
                        <p>Respectfully yours,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">G. von L. Meyer.</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>